1
00:03:50,787 --> 00:03:52,618
Hey, driver.

2
00:03:52,789 --> 00:03:55,155
Oh, happy Easter, Excellency.

3
00:03:55,325 --> 00:03:57,623
What is it you want, Stepal?
Could you drive to the Casbick

4
00:03:57,794 --> 00:03:59,694
And ask General Boynin
to come here immediately?

5
00:03:59,863 --> 00:04:03,196
Isn't it too late for the church
to save that master of yours?

6
00:04:03,366 --> 00:04:05,527
25 francs.
No. 10.

7
00:04:05,702 --> 00:04:09,331
On Easter night, 20.
15, Excellency.

8
00:04:09,506 --> 00:04:12,270
All right, Stepal. Happy Easter to you.

9
00:04:12,442 --> 00:04:13,466
Please, hurry.

10
00:04:13,643 --> 00:04:19,138
Leave it to me.
It's very urgent. Please.

11
00:04:37,133 --> 00:04:38,998
Don't you adore Russian food?

12
00:04:39,169 --> 00:04:41,194
Faster.

13
00:04:41,371 --> 00:04:43,566
Faster!

14
00:04:43,740 --> 00:04:46,208
Faster!
General,

15
00:04:46,376 --> 00:04:47,741
I'm just mad for your place.

16
00:04:47,911 --> 00:04:50,311
It's always a pleasure
to see you here, Madame.

17
00:04:50,480 --> 00:04:52,573
General Boynin, my husband.

18
00:04:52,749 --> 00:04:53,977
Excuse me, general.

19
00:04:54,150 --> 00:04:56,550
The count Periosov
is waiting outside in his taxi.

20
00:04:56,719 --> 00:04:58,084
He has a message for you.
From Stepal?

21
00:04:58,254 --> 00:05:00,119
Yes. He says it is urgent.

22
00:05:00,290 --> 00:05:02,224
I'll be right out.

23
00:05:02,392 --> 00:05:08,388
Will you forgive me for just a moment?

24
00:05:52,208 --> 00:05:53,869
Is she here?
Yes, sir.

25
00:05:54,043 --> 00:05:58,537
Where?
Over there by the tree.

26
00:05:59,048 --> 00:06:01,346
Are you sure?
Yes, Excellency.

27
00:06:01,518 --> 00:06:05,386
All right. Wait here.

28
00:06:05,555 --> 00:06:07,352
Happy Easter.

29
00:06:07,524 --> 00:06:09,492
Happy Easter, Anna Corev.

30
00:06:09,659 --> 00:06:10,853
It is Anna Corev?

31
00:06:11,027 --> 00:06:14,724
Or at least so you were called
in the asylum at St. Cluv.

32
00:06:14,898 --> 00:06:16,422
You see the resemblance?

33
00:06:16,599 --> 00:06:21,002
No more than 100 women might have.

34
00:06:21,170 --> 00:06:22,967
There is nothing to fear. I promise you.

35
00:06:23,139 --> 00:06:24,572
Why do you always run away?

36
00:06:24,741 --> 00:06:27,369
Always questions.
I have lost the answers.

37
00:06:27,544 --> 00:06:28,977
Perhaps if you hadn't told
a nun who you were,

38
00:06:29,145 --> 00:06:30,373
There wouldn't be any questions.

39
00:06:30,547 --> 00:06:35,041
Who am I?
Grand Duchess Anastasia, I believe.

40
00:06:35,318 --> 00:06:37,286
In an asylum, a nun might be mad.

41
00:06:37,453 --> 00:06:38,215
It's contagious.

42
00:06:38,388 --> 00:06:44,816
Then you do admit you were
in that asylum, don't you?

43
00:06:44,994 --> 00:06:46,928
Stepal, are you positive

44
00:06:47,096 --> 00:06:48,961
She is the same woman
you saw in St, Cluv?

45
00:06:49,132 --> 00:06:50,759
Yes, sir.

46
00:06:50,934 --> 00:06:53,926
Come on.

47
00:09:55,351 --> 00:10:00,880
Let me go. Please, let me go.

48
00:10:01,057 --> 00:10:04,254
The general said to wait for him
at the usual place.

49
00:10:04,427 --> 00:10:06,486
Wait! How do you like that?

50
00:10:06,662 --> 00:10:09,324
The nerve of that Boynin.
Didn't he leave us a message?

51
00:10:09,499 --> 00:10:15,062
Yes. He said he'd be back shortly.
Late. Always late.

52
00:10:15,238 --> 00:10:16,933
Petrovin, the hour has arrived for me...

53
00:10:17,106 --> 00:10:19,370
I know.

54
00:10:19,542 --> 00:10:22,170
You only tell me
what you are going to tell Boynin.

55
00:10:22,345 --> 00:10:24,609
Still, be happy now.

56
00:10:24,781 --> 00:10:26,749
In one week, you shall be
telling it in prison.

57
00:10:26,916 --> 00:10:29,544
Petrovin, I forbid that word.

58
00:10:29,719 --> 00:10:30,583
I didn't hear it.

59
00:10:30,753 --> 00:10:33,551
It's the logical end to what
was always a ridiculous scheme.

60
00:10:33,723 --> 00:10:35,384
Ridiculous scheme, huh?

61
00:10:35,558 --> 00:10:37,753
Well, your eyes lit up
like those of a mad monk

62
00:10:37,927 --> 00:10:40,191
When you heard our tsar's daughter
might be alive.

63
00:10:40,363 --> 00:10:40,727
That was ridiculous.

64
00:10:40,897 --> 00:10:44,128
And yours lit up when you heard
he had a 1o million inheritance.

65
00:10:44,300 --> 00:10:45,494
Equally ridiculous.

66
00:10:45,668 --> 00:10:46,692
Not equally.

67
00:10:46,869 --> 00:10:49,667
The 1o million lie waiting
in The Bank of England,

68
00:10:49,839 --> 00:10:53,366
But the Grand Duchess Anastasia
Nikolayevna lies buried in Russia.

69
00:10:53,543 --> 00:10:55,010
Vodka?
No, thank you.

70
00:10:55,178 --> 00:10:55,940
My indigestion has been shocking

71
00:10:56,112 --> 00:10:58,672
Ever since Boynin decided to
form our corporation.

72
00:10:58,848 --> 00:11:01,339
Boynin decided? The idea was mine.

73
00:11:01,517 --> 00:11:04,782
My years of banking experience
are for nothing?

74
00:11:04,954 --> 00:11:07,582
I devised the method of
setting Shestu stockholders

75
00:11:07,757 --> 00:11:11,124
To pay for the search for
their beloved grand duchess.

76
00:11:11,294 --> 00:11:14,058
I worked out the ratio
of so many shares in her inheritance

77
00:11:14,230 --> 00:11:16,027
To so many shares of our stock,

78
00:11:16,199 --> 00:11:18,224
And I... I know, Boynin was nothing.

79
00:11:18,401 --> 00:11:21,427
Boynin was nothing.

80
00:11:21,604 --> 00:11:23,469
Good evening, comrades.

81
00:11:23,639 --> 00:11:26,267
The term doesn't grate
on your white Russian ears.

82
00:11:26,442 --> 00:11:27,431
Huh?
Excuse me.

83
00:11:27,610 --> 00:11:30,238
Oh, I'm sorry.
The meeting is called to order.

84
00:11:30,413 --> 00:11:31,573
Called to order? Just like that?

85
00:11:31,747 --> 00:11:33,305
May we have the financial report,
please?

86
00:11:33,482 --> 00:11:35,109
The financial...
Yes, the financial report.

87
00:11:35,284 --> 00:11:36,216
There's another report, general.

88
00:11:36,385 --> 00:11:38,615
All in due time, Petrovanch.
Go ahead, Chernov.

89
00:11:38,788 --> 00:11:42,918
As of today,
our treasury shows assets...

90
00:11:43,092 --> 00:11:46,289
Of... here... exactly 5,25o francs.

91
00:11:46,462 --> 00:11:48,327
That new suit looks very well on you,
my dear Chernov.

92
00:11:48,497 --> 00:11:49,725
Am I wrong, or were there not

93
00:11:49,899 --> 00:11:52,060
Some 9,ooo-odd francs
at our last meeting?

94
00:11:52,235 --> 00:11:54,499
My dear general, may I ask you...

95
00:11:54,670 --> 00:11:57,264
May I ask you what paid
for this club of yours?

96
00:11:57,440 --> 00:12:00,341
15,ooo francs from the stockholders,
that's what.

97
00:12:00,509 --> 00:12:02,500
We live in one room,
Petrovin and I. Two.

98
00:12:02,678 --> 00:12:03,838
We share the bedroom.

99
00:12:04,013 --> 00:12:05,537
This is not a meeting
on your housing problem.

100
00:12:05,715 --> 00:12:10,778
Proceed with our accounts.
Housing problem. Hmmph!

101
00:12:10,953 --> 00:12:13,820
275 francs to Natalia Kovski,

102
00:12:13,990 --> 00:12:16,458
Formerly dressmaker
of the imperial family,

103
00:12:16,626 --> 00:12:19,493
Paid for the information I received
on clothes and measurements.

104
00:12:19,662 --> 00:12:21,220
I see you've made good use
of the information.

105
00:12:21,397 --> 00:12:23,627
I drew it myself.
Those are her exact measurements.

106
00:12:23,799 --> 00:12:27,462
The crown is a nice touch.
Yeah. A face would be a better one.

107
00:12:27,637 --> 00:12:29,832
It's all too late now.
We're facing disaster.

108
00:12:30,006 --> 00:12:32,600
As a son of the former deacon
to His Majesty's court,

109
00:12:32,775 --> 00:12:33,901
You should have more faith.

110
00:12:34,076 --> 00:12:37,045
I wish my poor father,
bless his soul, had had less.

111
00:12:37,213 --> 00:12:39,613
All right, Chernov. Please,
give him the news.

112
00:12:39,782 --> 00:12:41,841
I would rather have his first.

113
00:12:42,018 --> 00:12:44,282
Mine?
I know that smile.

114
00:12:44,453 --> 00:12:47,752
I'll bet you have another
Of your brilliant surprises for us.

115
00:12:47,924 --> 00:12:49,391
Never mind. What happened, Petrovin?

116
00:12:49,558 --> 00:12:52,789
Chernov... I was summoned by
the stockholders' committee.

117
00:12:52,962 --> 00:12:54,554
Oh? How kind of them.

118
00:12:54,730 --> 00:12:55,958
Kind, eh?

119
00:12:56,132 --> 00:12:58,623
The old General Anikin
came straight to the point.

120
00:12:58,801 --> 00:13:00,063
"Years ago," he said,

121
00:13:00,236 --> 00:13:03,933
"Rumors started that the Grand Duchess
Anastasia Nikolayevna,

122
00:13:04,106 --> 00:13:06,404
"Daughter of His Imperial Majesty
Nicholas II,

123
00:13:06,575 --> 00:13:09,169
"Had not been murdered
with the rest of the royal family,

124
00:13:09,345 --> 00:13:11,370
"But had escaped miraculously.

125
00:13:11,547 --> 00:13:13,014
A year ago," he went on,

126
00:13:13,182 --> 00:13:15,173
"You and your friends
came to us with a claim

127
00:13:15,351 --> 00:13:17,945
"You knew Her Highness
was somewhere in Berlin.

128
00:13:18,120 --> 00:13:20,384
Then you said you found her,
but she ran away."

129
00:13:20,556 --> 00:13:22,217
Was it then we thought
of using the redhead?

130
00:13:22,391 --> 00:13:23,722
No. No. The one who was always giggling.

131
00:13:23,893 --> 00:13:25,952
Ah, yes. The redhead came later.
Go ahead.

132
00:13:26,128 --> 00:13:29,063
Then he said,
"you needed more money to find her.

133
00:13:29,231 --> 00:13:30,789
"Again we subscribed.

134
00:13:30,967 --> 00:13:35,233
"Then you said you found her,
but she was too sick.

135
00:13:35,404 --> 00:13:36,928
More money."
Too sick? That was galena... too stupid.

136
00:13:37,106 --> 00:13:38,539
"How long can she be sick, Chernov?

137
00:13:38,708 --> 00:13:41,233
How much money can you drain
from our thin pockets, Chernov?"

138
00:13:41,410 --> 00:13:42,377
How much have they got, Chernov?

139
00:13:42,545 --> 00:13:46,140
The joke is on us, general.
They give us exactly eight days.

140
00:13:46,315 --> 00:13:47,407
Eight days for what?

141
00:13:47,583 --> 00:13:50,484
Eight days to produce Her Highness,
the Grand Duchess Anastasia.

142
00:13:50,653 --> 00:13:54,680
Or we go to prison for fraud!
Well, it has taken them long enough.

143
00:13:54,857 --> 00:13:55,755
Is that all you can say?

144
00:13:55,925 --> 00:13:57,916
It sickens me how you
let him make you suffer.

145
00:13:58,094 --> 00:13:59,254
How you like to suffer,

146
00:13:59,428 --> 00:14:02,397
And you delight in making him suffer.
Not particularly.

147
00:14:02,565 --> 00:14:04,590
I merely thought it
advisable to determine

148
00:14:04,767 --> 00:14:06,564
Exactly what our situation was

149
00:14:06,736 --> 00:14:08,169
Before suggesting how to deal with it.

150
00:14:08,337 --> 00:14:10,703
What did I tell you? All right,
general, let's have your surprise.

151
00:14:10,873 --> 00:14:11,965
Where is she?
Where is who?

152
00:14:12,141 --> 00:14:14,439
The woman Stepal saw
in the asylum at St. Cluv.

153
00:14:14,610 --> 00:14:16,840
Correct.
We have finally tracked her down.

154
00:14:17,013 --> 00:14:18,173
Really?

155
00:14:18,347 --> 00:14:19,974
Of course, she does not admit
that she was there.

156
00:14:20,149 --> 00:14:21,138
Really?

157
00:14:21,317 --> 00:14:23,342
Nor does she admit that
she told a nun there

158
00:14:23,519 --> 00:14:25,544
That she was the tsar's daughter.
What does she admit?

159
00:14:25,721 --> 00:14:27,188
Nothing.
Then why do you believe...

160
00:14:27,356 --> 00:14:29,324
I think she may be lying,
But the important thing is that,

161
00:14:29,492 --> 00:14:31,289
Properly used,
she may serve our purpose.

162
00:14:31,460 --> 00:14:34,122
How?
She has certain surprising features.

163
00:14:34,296 --> 00:14:35,092
Such as?

164
00:14:35,264 --> 00:14:39,633
You will see. She also has
a rather intriguing strangeness

165
00:14:39,802 --> 00:14:42,134
Of course, that may simply be
the result of amnesia.

166
00:14:42,304 --> 00:14:43,601
Him and his surprises.

167
00:14:43,773 --> 00:14:47,174
If he were looking for a grand duke,
he wouldn't find so many.

168
00:14:47,343 --> 00:14:48,435
Stepal,

169
00:14:48,611 --> 00:14:51,603
Bring her in.

170
00:14:53,616 --> 00:14:57,609
Come over here.

171
00:15:00,356 --> 00:15:04,850
Don't worry.
These two gentlemen are friends.

172
00:15:07,863 --> 00:15:11,458
Here. Sit down.

173
00:15:11,634 --> 00:15:14,296
How about a glass of vodka?
It will do you good.

174
00:15:14,470 --> 00:15:17,462
Thank you.

175
00:15:18,274 --> 00:15:20,742
There's nothing to fear.
They merely want to examine you.

176
00:15:20,910 --> 00:15:23,470
Examine? Are they doctors?

177
00:15:23,646 --> 00:15:27,776
Well, they don't help.
Doctors? No, they are not doctors.

178
00:15:27,950 --> 00:15:30,248
No. No. We should have kept the redhead.

179
00:15:30,419 --> 00:15:32,887
That tsar's daughter
drinks like a cossack.

180
00:15:33,055 --> 00:15:39,551
May I have a cigarette?
Sure. Here.

181
00:15:44,567 --> 00:15:47,502
Where am I?
I told you, with friends.

182
00:15:47,670 --> 00:15:49,365
Strange.
What?

183
00:15:49,538 --> 00:15:52,871
The resemblance to the other.
Yes, both female.

184
00:15:53,042 --> 00:15:55,169
Have you gentlemen considered
what she went through?

185
00:15:55,344 --> 00:15:57,141
The streets, probably.

186
00:15:57,313 --> 00:15:59,213
I can imagine her walk.

187
00:15:59,381 --> 00:16:00,780
Stand up.

188
00:16:00,950 --> 00:16:04,545
What did you say?
Oh, ho ho! I said stand up.

189
00:16:04,720 --> 00:16:06,278
We would like to see you
walk over to there,

190
00:16:06,455 --> 00:16:09,447
If you please.

191
00:16:14,163 --> 00:16:15,391
No. At least with the redhead,

192
00:16:15,564 --> 00:16:18,226
We could have dyed her hair,
but a walk...

193
00:16:18,400 --> 00:16:19,560
The grand duchesses learned

194
00:16:19,735 --> 00:16:21,032
With books on their heads.

195
00:16:21,203 --> 00:16:26,334
You could recognize them
by their carriage alone.

196
00:16:26,509 --> 00:16:29,137
Stone walls.
What's she talking about?

197
00:16:29,311 --> 00:16:31,939
Chernov, that bookkeeper
who nearly ruined you

198
00:16:32,114 --> 00:16:33,638
12 years ago in the forgery affair,

199
00:16:33,816 --> 00:16:35,477
Would you recognize his walk today?

200
00:16:35,651 --> 00:16:38,017
Would you recognize the smile
of a girl you knew 1o years ago?

201
00:16:38,187 --> 00:16:40,485
I didn't think of that.
You are both fools.

202
00:16:40,656 --> 00:16:42,749
You are examining her
as if she was the real Anastasia.

203
00:16:42,925 --> 00:16:44,552
There is no Anastasia.

204
00:16:44,727 --> 00:16:47,696
She was shot to death
1 years ago by a firing squad.

205
00:16:47,863 --> 00:16:49,592
We are not looking for her, gentlemen.

206
00:16:49,765 --> 00:16:51,960
We are seeking
only a reasonable facsimile.

207
00:16:52,134 --> 00:16:53,795
Reasonable, yes,
but that is unreasonable.

208
00:16:53,969 --> 00:16:55,630
Please, let's be constructive.

209
00:16:55,804 --> 00:16:57,169
Besides, what will the committee say?

210
00:16:57,339 --> 00:16:58,772
Most of them have seen the original.

211
00:16:58,941 --> 00:17:01,102
How? At a court ball from a balcony?

212
00:17:01,277 --> 00:17:03,643
In church by candlelight,
flickering shadows?

213
00:17:03,812 --> 00:17:05,609
Yes, you saw her. Many saw her

214
00:17:05,781 --> 00:17:07,544
From a distance or in the newspapers.
What about the servants?

215
00:17:07,716 --> 00:17:08,842
Some of them are here in exile.

216
00:17:09,018 --> 00:17:11,077
They saw her through devoted tears,
and they will again.

217
00:17:11,253 --> 00:17:12,311
All right. Then the family?

218
00:17:12,488 --> 00:17:13,284
The family?

219
00:17:13,455 --> 00:17:15,514
If it was the immediate family,
I would not try,

220
00:17:15,691 --> 00:17:16,589
But they are dead,

221
00:17:16,759 --> 00:17:19,193
And do you have faith in the memories
of uncles, aunts, cousins?

222
00:17:19,361 --> 00:17:21,022
I don't.
You have faith in nothing.

223
00:17:21,197 --> 00:17:23,062
They will closet themselves
in their bedrooms

224
00:17:23,232 --> 00:17:25,200
And secretly peer at yellow photographs

225
00:17:25,367 --> 00:17:25,958
Which that woman will resemble.

226
00:17:26,135 --> 00:17:27,864
That?
Yes, that.

227
00:17:28,037 --> 00:17:29,902
Rouge will turn the mouth up a bit.

228
00:17:30,072 --> 00:17:32,063
Some powder, a new coiffure,

229
00:17:32,241 --> 00:17:35,608
Dresses to suggest the other period,
walk, manner, voice

230
00:17:35,778 --> 00:17:38,372
Taught along with faces, names, places.

231
00:17:38,547 --> 00:17:39,514
It would be easier

232
00:17:39,682 --> 00:17:43,277
If I could present her to the committee
lying in her coffin.

233
00:17:43,452 --> 00:17:46,353
Yes... no questions, no answers,
no mistakes.

234
00:17:46,522 --> 00:17:49,753
No money, either.
I know. Now I know.

235
00:17:49,925 --> 00:17:52,052
Know what?
It's a cellar.

236
00:17:52,228 --> 00:17:53,456
You brought me down here to shoot me.

237
00:17:53,629 --> 00:17:54,755
Are you mad?
It's a cellar!

238
00:17:54,930 --> 00:17:56,557
This is absurd. Sit down!
No.

239
00:17:56,732 --> 00:17:59,929
Sit down, I said!

240
00:18:00,102 --> 00:18:03,094
Ha ha ha! Pretty good. Pretty good.

241
00:18:03,272 --> 00:18:05,172
A little more rehearsal, perhaps.

242
00:18:05,341 --> 00:18:05,932
What?

243
00:18:06,108 --> 00:18:08,975
He told her how the real one
was shot in a cellar...

244
00:18:09,144 --> 00:18:11,772
Don't be stupid. I told her nothing.

245
00:18:11,947 --> 00:18:13,744
The woman can undoubtedly read,

246
00:18:13,916 --> 00:18:15,008
And certainly enough has been written

247
00:18:15,184 --> 00:18:16,981
Describing their death in the cellar.

248
00:18:17,152 --> 00:18:20,178
Some say she did not die.

249
00:18:20,356 --> 00:18:22,119
Where did you get that?

250
00:18:22,291 --> 00:18:24,384
He just said so... from a book,

251
00:18:24,560 --> 00:18:27,620
Or a story I was told
or a rumor, a whisper.

252
00:18:27,796 --> 00:18:29,229
Or it... it happened.

253
00:18:29,398 --> 00:18:31,958
It did not, and that woman
is too something...

254
00:18:32,134 --> 00:18:34,295
Too crazy, too clever, too tricky.

255
00:18:34,470 --> 00:18:37,166
I don't care what she is.
The important thing is that she fits.

256
00:18:37,339 --> 00:18:41,332
Get up. Go over there.

257
00:18:44,813 --> 00:18:49,079
What is it?
Just a drawing. Stand closer.

258
00:18:49,251 --> 00:18:52,243
Turn around.

259
00:18:53,956 --> 00:18:55,218
The correct height.

260
00:18:55,391 --> 00:19:00,886
The correct height.
Yes. The crown might belong on her head.

261
00:19:01,497 --> 00:19:04,523
A drawing of whom? Who is it?

262
00:19:04,700 --> 00:19:08,397
A princess, a Russian grand duchess
who died in 1918.

263
00:19:08,570 --> 00:19:13,064
A princess?
Ha ha ha ha!

264
00:19:16,011 --> 00:19:18,036
Petrovin, a glass of water.

265
00:19:18,213 --> 00:19:19,111
It's all right.

266
00:19:19,281 --> 00:19:22,341
It's all right, Petrovin.
Her Highness is better.

267
00:19:22,518 --> 00:19:25,146
Don't call me that!
How well you hear,

268
00:19:25,321 --> 00:19:27,812
And how well you know how to use
what you hear, and when.

269
00:19:27,990 --> 00:19:29,048
It was you who told the nun

270
00:19:29,224 --> 00:19:30,714
That you were
the Grand Duchess Anastasia.

271
00:19:30,893 --> 00:19:32,224
Sick people get sick ideas.

272
00:19:32,394 --> 00:19:33,952
Then you were in that asylum
in St. Cluv.

273
00:19:34,129 --> 00:19:36,859
And before that, in Berlin.

274
00:19:37,032 --> 00:19:38,897
Let me out of here!
You know you were.

275
00:19:39,068 --> 00:19:40,865
You were, and you weren't.
Why and why not...

276
00:19:41,036 --> 00:19:43,436
Questions like that can only be
answered by lies! Let me go!

277
00:19:43,605 --> 00:19:47,598
Stop it! Stop it!

278
00:19:48,177 --> 00:19:50,338
No.
No.

279
00:19:50,512 --> 00:19:54,004
Please. Please.
Don't! Don't!

280
00:19:54,183 --> 00:19:55,775
Look at her hand.
What?

281
00:19:55,951 --> 00:19:59,785
Go on. Look.
Well, he wants us to look. All right.

282
00:19:59,955 --> 00:20:03,152
Come. Now, come under the light.

283
00:20:03,325 --> 00:20:05,350
Sit down.

284
00:20:05,527 --> 00:20:09,293
Open your hands.

285
00:20:09,465 --> 00:20:11,456
I told you there were
surprising features.

286
00:20:11,633 --> 00:20:14,500
On the palm of each hand, a scar.
As from bullets?

287
00:20:14,670 --> 00:20:18,071
Now look at her head,
above the left temple...

288
00:20:18,240 --> 00:20:20,765
A narrow depression extending
almost to the forehead.

289
00:20:20,943 --> 00:20:22,308
Just as we were told.

290
00:20:22,478 --> 00:20:25,345
Where did you get those scars?

291
00:20:25,514 --> 00:20:27,812
A gift from an unknown admirer.

292
00:20:27,983 --> 00:20:30,110
Where?

293
00:20:30,285 --> 00:20:31,582
I don't remember.

294
00:20:31,754 --> 00:20:33,779
Wounds like that,
and you don't remember?

295
00:20:33,956 --> 00:20:36,288
Who are you?

296
00:20:36,458 --> 00:20:38,392
No one.
Who are your parents?

297
00:20:38,560 --> 00:20:40,425
None.
Where are you from?

298
00:20:40,596 --> 00:20:42,621
The river.
Before that?

299
00:20:42,798 --> 00:20:45,460
A madhouse.
And before that?

300
00:20:45,634 --> 00:20:49,468
Another river and another madhouse.
Come on, now. Who are you?

301
00:20:49,638 --> 00:20:52,072
You tell me.
You must be someone.

302
00:20:52,241 --> 00:20:53,731
Why?

303
00:20:53,909 --> 00:20:56,002
Nobody, nothing, no one.
Incredible.

304
00:20:56,178 --> 00:20:57,645
But most convenient for us.

305
00:20:57,813 --> 00:20:59,713
All right, gentlemen, come over here.

306
00:20:59,882 --> 00:21:01,179
Add up the facts...

307
00:21:01,350 --> 00:21:03,716
One, she has a certain resemblance,
which we can heighten.

308
00:21:03,886 --> 00:21:07,617
Two, she's obviously smart enough
to learn what we teach.

309
00:21:07,790 --> 00:21:10,020
Discrepancies in her memory
can be attributed to the head wound.

310
00:21:10,192 --> 00:21:13,161
Three, she has no identity whatsoever,

311
00:21:13,328 --> 00:21:14,989
Which means it will be
exceedingly difficult

312
00:21:15,164 --> 00:21:16,859
For anyone to prove that
she's someone else.

313
00:21:17,032 --> 00:21:18,363
Four...
We have eight days.

314
00:21:18,534 --> 00:21:21,230
Precisely. All in favor of
the candidate...

315
00:21:21,403 --> 00:21:24,497
Two to one. Elected.
Two to one. Elected.

316
00:21:24,673 --> 00:21:27,608
Do you realize there are
1o million at stake!

317
00:21:27,776 --> 00:21:29,903
1o million?
Yes, my dear.

318
00:21:30,078 --> 00:21:31,602
The inheritance of 1o million

319
00:21:31,780 --> 00:21:34,010
Left by the tsar in The Bank of England,

320
00:21:34,183 --> 00:21:36,344
And you want to risk it on a madwoman.

321
00:21:36,518 --> 00:21:38,213
I must still be in the asylum

322
00:21:38,387 --> 00:21:40,753
With the one who sat covered
and crouched on the floor

323
00:21:40,923 --> 00:21:42,584
Because she wasn't born yet.

324
00:21:42,758 --> 00:21:45,420
It's you who are mad!
I'll have no part of this!

325
00:21:45,594 --> 00:21:46,686
Now, now, my dear.

326
00:21:46,862 --> 00:21:49,160
The carriage of the head
not quite so high.

327
00:21:49,331 --> 00:21:50,320
Grand duchesses are proud

328
00:21:50,499 --> 00:21:53,059
But also modest.
They are to be killed, not to be sold!

329
00:21:53,235 --> 00:21:55,931
There you are, mad as a hatter.

330
00:21:56,104 --> 00:21:58,038
Now she really thinks she is Anastasia.

331
00:21:58,207 --> 00:21:59,401
I do not. I am not.

332
00:21:59,575 --> 00:22:00,701
But you can be.
I can make you Anastasia.

333
00:22:00,876 --> 00:22:02,741
She's dead. You said so yourself.
That doesn't matter.

334
00:22:02,911 --> 00:22:04,310
Please. Please. No one will believe it.

335
00:22:04,480 --> 00:22:05,606
The family, they call the lie.

336
00:22:05,781 --> 00:22:07,043
No matter what they think,
they will accept you.

337
00:22:07,216 --> 00:22:09,480
For 1o million, gladly.

338
00:22:09,651 --> 00:22:11,778
They would accept me
and pretend to love me for money?

339
00:22:11,954 --> 00:22:13,319
Is that what they are like?
Isn't everyone?

340
00:22:13,489 --> 00:22:16,356
No. I'm going.
Where? To the river or the madhouse?

341
00:22:16,525 --> 00:22:19,255
You have no papers.
The police will pick you up soon enough.

342
00:22:19,428 --> 00:22:22,829
If you don't die of starvation sooner.
Oh, come, come. Why, then,

343
00:22:22,998 --> 00:22:25,193
Did you tell those stories
in the hospital?

344
00:22:25,367 --> 00:22:27,062
To the little nun?

345
00:22:27,236 --> 00:22:30,728
Her eyes grew big as a child's,
but then in the evening,

346
00:22:30,906 --> 00:22:32,999
She brought me special things to eat...

347
00:22:33,175 --> 00:22:34,403
An orange or some grapes.

348
00:22:34,576 --> 00:22:35,804
We can bring you much more.

349
00:22:35,978 --> 00:22:38,071
But in another hospital,
I told other stories,

350
00:22:38,247 --> 00:22:40,181
And they believed them, too,

351
00:22:40,349 --> 00:22:43,113
Especially the one
where the train blew up.

352
00:22:43,285 --> 00:22:46,152
We were too close to
where the mine was planted,

353
00:22:46,321 --> 00:22:48,255
So when the train hit it,

354
00:22:48,423 --> 00:22:51,483
Pieces of metal fell
like a shower of fireworks

355
00:22:51,660 --> 00:22:53,252
All about us.

356
00:22:53,428 --> 00:22:58,491
The man beside me was killed,
and the man beside him, too,

357
00:22:58,667 --> 00:23:00,396
But I was only wounded.

358
00:23:00,569 --> 00:23:04,767
Oh, so that's how you got those scars.

359
00:23:04,940 --> 00:23:06,464
Yes. So it would seem.

360
00:23:06,642 --> 00:23:09,008
I thought you couldn't remember.

361
00:23:09,177 --> 00:23:14,444
I can't always. Things come and go,
like waves of mist.

362
00:23:14,616 --> 00:23:16,777
But, look, to be her is what you want,
what we want,

363
00:23:16,952 --> 00:23:19,216
Even what the royal family wants.

364
00:23:19,388 --> 00:23:21,322
So I've heard before. All of it...

365
00:23:21,490 --> 00:23:23,549
"Say this. Remember that.
You are. You are not.

366
00:23:23,725 --> 00:23:25,249
I know you, I don't know you."

367
00:23:25,427 --> 00:23:28,055
Oh, I've heard it many times.
Where?

368
00:23:28,230 --> 00:23:29,857
Bucharest, Berlin...

369
00:23:30,032 --> 00:23:30,498
Berlin?

370
00:23:30,666 --> 00:23:35,069
Or china! I don't remember,
but the enthusiasm and the promise,

371
00:23:35,237 --> 00:23:39,105
It's those I remember,
and then when memory failed,

372
00:23:39,274 --> 00:23:43,335
Disappointment, anger, dismissal.

373
00:23:43,512 --> 00:23:47,380
Out in the street...
failure! Fake! Nobody!

374
00:23:47,549 --> 00:23:48,538
There you are wrong.

375
00:23:48,717 --> 00:23:50,651
There will not be failure this time,
not with me.

376
00:23:50,819 --> 00:23:56,155
Now, listen, you want to know
who you are, don't you?

377
00:23:56,325 --> 00:23:57,257
Oh, yes.

378
00:23:57,426 --> 00:24:01,294
You want to find the family
to whom you belong, don't you?

379
00:24:01,463 --> 00:24:03,624
Yes. Yes.

380
00:24:03,799 --> 00:24:06,393
By yourself, you are lost,
but with me, you'll find yourself.

381
00:24:06,568 --> 00:24:08,263
Oh, please. I'm tired.

382
00:24:08,437 --> 00:24:09,426
You know I am right.

383
00:24:09,605 --> 00:24:12,938
The album... take the chance.
It's the only one you have.

384
00:24:13,108 --> 00:24:14,370
I'm too tired to argue.

385
00:24:14,543 --> 00:24:21,039
You don't have to do anything.
I will do it all. Now, here, look.

386
00:24:21,216 --> 00:24:23,741
It's you on the deck
of your father's yacht.

387
00:24:23,919 --> 00:24:26,012
The Standart.
The Standart?

388
00:24:26,188 --> 00:24:27,951
You know the name?

389
00:24:28,123 --> 00:24:30,148
It's written on the lifeboat.

390
00:24:30,325 --> 00:24:33,317
Oh, yes.
Now, here you are with your family...

391
00:24:33,495 --> 00:24:36,157
Your father the tsar,
your mother, your sisters,

392
00:24:36,331 --> 00:24:38,925
Your little brother.
My family.

393
00:24:39,101 --> 00:24:40,591
And here...

394
00:24:40,769 --> 00:24:42,794
Look.

395
00:24:42,971 --> 00:24:45,633
1913, the anniversary
of the house of Romanov...

396
00:24:45,807 --> 00:24:47,138
3oo years.

397
00:24:47,309 --> 00:24:49,834
There they are on the balcony
of the winter palace,

398
00:24:50,012 --> 00:24:53,140
And that little girl there, that is you.

399
00:24:53,315 --> 00:24:54,373
Thousands kneeling.

400
00:24:54,549 --> 00:24:56,176
Singing god save the tsar.

401
00:24:56,351 --> 00:24:58,751
The people. Your people.

402
00:24:58,920 --> 00:25:00,319
Yes.

403
00:25:00,489 --> 00:25:03,390
You can see it, can't you?
Yes, I can.

404
00:25:03,558 --> 00:25:05,355
Now, may I present your staff?

405
00:25:05,527 --> 00:25:08,394
Belis Andreis Chernov,
formerly of St. Petersburg,

406
00:25:08,563 --> 00:25:10,190
Banker.

407
00:25:10,365 --> 00:25:14,426
Petrovanch Petrovin, former student
of the theological seminary.

408
00:25:14,603 --> 00:25:17,697
Sergei Pavlovich Boynin,
general of the Chekist regiment,

409
00:25:17,873 --> 00:25:18,635
Former aide-de-camp

410
00:25:18,807 --> 00:25:21,469
Attached to the person
of His Imperial Majesty Nicholas II,

411
00:25:21,643 --> 00:25:24,544
Tsar of all Russia.

412
00:25:24,713 --> 00:25:26,305
And I am...

413
00:25:26,481 --> 00:25:29,279
I am Her Imperial Highness,

414
00:25:29,451 --> 00:25:32,511
The Grand Duchess Anastasia Nikolayevna.

415
00:25:32,688 --> 00:25:36,681
Ha ha ha ha ha!

416
00:25:47,502 --> 00:25:50,369
Now, once more.

417
00:25:50,539 --> 00:25:52,404
Awakened in the middle of the night

418
00:25:52,574 --> 00:25:55,509
And taken down to the cellar...
And then, without warning...

419
00:25:55,677 --> 00:25:59,511
Guards appeared in the doorway
and began firing,

420
00:25:59,681 --> 00:26:02,707
But one fainted, shielded
by the body of her sister...

421
00:26:02,884 --> 00:26:04,647
Which sister?

422
00:26:04,820 --> 00:26:07,050
Was it Olga?
Right.

423
00:26:07,222 --> 00:26:10,953
Yes. Her white dress, then darkness.

424
00:26:11,126 --> 00:26:15,153
One of the executioners
crashed down with his rifle.

425
00:26:15,330 --> 00:26:17,298
Later two brothers were among the guards

426
00:26:17,466 --> 00:26:21,095
That came into the cellar
to remove the dead.

427
00:26:21,269 --> 00:26:22,736
One of the bodies moved.

428
00:26:22,904 --> 00:26:26,635
Hers.
Hidden in a farm cart under straw,

429
00:26:26,808 --> 00:26:30,710
Wrapped in sheets filled
with snow for her fever,

430
00:26:30,879 --> 00:26:33,211
They fled across the country,

431
00:26:33,381 --> 00:26:36,043
Bribed guards with jewels
sewn into her blouse.

432
00:26:36,218 --> 00:26:37,845
Skirt.

433
00:26:38,019 --> 00:26:42,285
Was it?
And they made their way to?

434
00:26:42,457 --> 00:26:43,389
I don't know.

435
00:26:43,558 --> 00:26:45,355
Balta.
Balta.

436
00:26:45,527 --> 00:26:49,395
And from there across
the Romanian border to?

437
00:26:49,564 --> 00:26:52,692
Bucharest.
And there?

438
00:26:52,868 --> 00:26:55,860
There...

439
00:26:57,005 --> 00:27:01,066
There she died of heartbreak
and was thrown into the sea

440
00:27:01,243 --> 00:27:04,337
To the strains of an old Russian waltz.

441
00:27:04,513 --> 00:27:07,004
It was all quite good up to the end.

442
00:27:07,182 --> 00:27:10,583
This icon... you are supposed
to have seen it before.

443
00:27:10,752 --> 00:27:12,219
Remember? Where was it?

444
00:27:12,387 --> 00:27:13,786
In my mother's bedroom.

445
00:27:13,955 --> 00:27:16,651
She was very religious,
and she placed holy pictures everywhere.

446
00:27:16,825 --> 00:27:20,283
Right.
And books and albums just like these,

447
00:27:20,462 --> 00:27:22,430
Scattered about, overflowing the tables,

448
00:27:22,597 --> 00:27:24,565
And there was a sitting room

449
00:27:24,733 --> 00:27:28,134
Between the bedroom
of my mother and my fa...

450
00:27:28,303 --> 00:27:30,294
Oh, no. That was that little
reading room in the hospital.

451
00:27:30,472 --> 00:27:32,997
Oh, how silly.
More coffee? She won't sleep.

452
00:27:33,175 --> 00:27:34,699
She hasn't got time to sleep.

453
00:27:34,876 --> 00:27:38,277
I don't very much anyway, but thank you.

454
00:27:38,446 --> 00:27:40,175
All right, where were we?

455
00:27:40,348 --> 00:27:43,112
Oh, yes. Your mother.

456
00:27:43,285 --> 00:27:44,582
But I know what I am talking about.

457
00:27:44,753 --> 00:27:46,345
We have exactly three days left.

458
00:27:46,521 --> 00:27:48,386
Let us worry about one thing at a time.

459
00:27:48,557 --> 00:27:50,718
"One thing at a time."

460
00:27:50,892 --> 00:27:52,189
All right, Petrovanch, I'll take over.

461
00:27:52,360 --> 00:27:55,386
I think she's very tired.
I've had my coffee.

462
00:27:55,564 --> 00:27:58,032
Besides, it all helps to
bring my memory back,

463
00:27:58,200 --> 00:28:00,964
And maybe one memory
will convince someone,

464
00:28:01,136 --> 00:28:03,604
Even if it's only me.

465
00:28:03,772 --> 00:28:05,296
Where did you live in the winter?

466
00:28:05,473 --> 00:28:07,407
The winter palace, St. Petersburg.

467
00:28:07,576 --> 00:28:09,669
Right. Spring?

468
00:28:09,845 --> 00:28:10,709
Spring?

469
00:28:10,879 --> 00:28:13,313
I don't remember.
Tsarskoe Selo.

470
00:28:13,481 --> 00:28:16,450
Tsarskoe Selo.
Summer?

471
00:28:16,618 --> 00:28:19,212
Peterhof, Livadia...

472
00:28:19,387 --> 00:28:21,878
Preferred for the sea air.
Hunting season?

473
00:28:22,057 --> 00:28:23,149
Spala.

474
00:28:23,325 --> 00:28:25,816
Where?
In Poland.

475
00:28:25,994 --> 00:28:27,222
Petrovanch.

476
00:28:27,395 --> 00:28:29,260
And on the Baltic?

477
00:28:29,431 --> 00:28:31,399
No luck, general. The committee...

478
00:28:31,566 --> 00:28:32,931
In Moscow, you stayed...

479
00:28:33,101 --> 00:28:34,568
At the Kremlin.

480
00:28:34,736 --> 00:28:35,964
Sergei Pavlovich, no.

481
00:28:36,137 --> 00:28:38,970
The committee will not
give us even one more day.

482
00:28:39,140 --> 00:28:41,938
You think she's ready?
No. Of course, she thinks she is.

483
00:28:42,110 --> 00:28:44,738
Listen, she thinks she's Anastasia,

484
00:28:44,913 --> 00:28:46,744
And the great Stanislaviski once said,

485
00:28:46,915 --> 00:28:48,610
"When an actor believes he is

486
00:28:48,783 --> 00:28:50,978
The character he's playing, fire him."
It's a bit late for that.

487
00:28:51,152 --> 00:28:52,551
Well, it's a bit late for anything.

488
00:28:52,721 --> 00:28:55,417
The eight days are finished.
The play is finished.

489
00:28:55,590 --> 00:28:56,750
We are finished.

490
00:28:56,925 --> 00:28:58,916
The play is merely
replaced by a pantomime.

491
00:28:59,094 --> 00:29:02,586
Our leading lady will be very weak,
exhausted, too sick to talk.

492
00:29:02,764 --> 00:29:04,823
With careful staging,
the committee will be satisfied.

493
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:06,365
And careful casting.

494
00:29:06,534 --> 00:29:08,900
Her Imperial Highness
will be too weak to see

495
00:29:09,070 --> 00:29:11,538
Any more than, let us say, six members.

496
00:29:11,706 --> 00:29:12,468
Why six?

497
00:29:12,641 --> 00:29:15,439
Three stupid enough
to accept even you as Anastasia.

498
00:29:15,610 --> 00:29:20,479
Three important enough to spread
the news that she is Anastasia.

499
00:29:20,649 --> 00:29:23,516
Your Highness, may I present
a few members of our colony here,

500
00:29:23,685 --> 00:29:26,848
Who, as I told you, are anxious
to see you for just a moment.

501
00:29:27,022 --> 00:29:30,116
His Excellency
Count Ilia Feodorovich Bikhmetev

502
00:29:30,292 --> 00:29:33,750
And his brother,
Count Andrei Feodorovich Bikhmetev,

503
00:29:33,929 --> 00:29:37,490
His Excellency Count Assessor Shushken.

504
00:29:37,666 --> 00:29:41,500
Shushken.
What?

505
00:29:41,670 --> 00:29:43,968
Your Imperial Highness.

506
00:29:44,139 --> 00:29:50,135
His Excellency Von Bridnetz.

507
00:29:53,315 --> 00:29:55,374
It's very rude to stare.

508
00:29:55,550 --> 00:29:57,643
Forgive me.

509
00:29:57,819 --> 00:29:59,184
Difficult to say.

510
00:29:59,354 --> 00:30:03,347
Madame Deresianskaia.

511
00:30:05,060 --> 00:30:06,459
Come closer.

512
00:30:06,628 --> 00:30:10,621
No. You, please.

513
00:30:11,800 --> 00:30:13,392
I think I know you.

514
00:30:13,568 --> 00:30:15,832
Were you not a lady-in-waiting
To my mother?

515
00:30:16,004 --> 00:30:18,700
Many people know that, I'm afraid.

516
00:30:18,873 --> 00:30:21,239
I'm trying to remember more.

517
00:30:21,409 --> 00:30:22,706
When I was a child, I used to watch

518
00:30:22,877 --> 00:30:24,811
The faces of the ladies- In-waiting

519
00:30:24,980 --> 00:30:26,470
To see if they were wearing lip rouge.

520
00:30:26,648 --> 00:30:29,708
My mother did not allow make-up, so I...

521
00:30:29,884 --> 00:30:37,381
I was not mean, just mischievous
I used to report to her.

522
00:30:39,594 --> 00:30:42,119
What was it my mother used to call you?

523
00:30:42,297 --> 00:30:46,290
Sura, um... Zena...

524
00:30:47,002 --> 00:30:50,597
I'm sorry. It escapes my...

525
00:30:50,772 --> 00:30:52,239
Nini.

526
00:30:52,407 --> 00:30:54,204
Yes, Nini.

527
00:30:54,376 --> 00:31:00,372
Your Highness. Your Imperial Highness.

528
00:31:09,891 --> 00:31:10,687
What's the matter?

529
00:31:10,859 --> 00:31:12,292
Don't you like my borscht?

530
00:31:12,460 --> 00:31:13,154
No.

531
00:31:13,328 --> 00:31:15,956
Too bad.
The general says you have to eat it.

532
00:31:16,131 --> 00:31:19,032
She won't eat!
All right, go.

533
00:31:19,200 --> 00:31:20,064
This entire household,

534
00:31:20,235 --> 00:31:22,362
Everything has been turned
upside down just for you,

535
00:31:22,537 --> 00:31:24,129
To make you comfortable,
to help you get well.

536
00:31:24,305 --> 00:31:25,101
I don't like borscht.

537
00:31:25,273 --> 00:31:27,673
I don't care whether
you like it or not! Eat it!

538
00:31:27,842 --> 00:31:29,935
I specifically warned you
not to say one word to that committee.

539
00:31:30,111 --> 00:31:31,976
You could have ruined everything.

540
00:31:32,147 --> 00:31:33,546
I told you about Nini, didn't I?

541
00:31:33,715 --> 00:31:35,148
Maybe. I don't know.

542
00:31:35,316 --> 00:31:37,250
Yes, I did or Petrovin did
or you overheard us,

543
00:31:37,419 --> 00:31:38,181
But the important thing...

544
00:31:38,353 --> 00:31:40,981
Are you angry because you're
beginning to wonder who I am

545
00:31:41,156 --> 00:31:43,454
Or because you want me to do nothing
except what you tell me?

546
00:31:43,625 --> 00:31:45,058
I know who you are not,

547
00:31:45,226 --> 00:31:46,716
Just as I know that
unless you do as I tell you,

548
00:31:46,895 --> 00:31:49,159
I'll have an extra cigarette girl
at my club.

549
00:31:49,330 --> 00:31:51,457
We now have a breathing spell
we need badly.

550
00:31:51,633 --> 00:31:52,395
You still have a great deal to learn

551
00:31:52,567 --> 00:31:53,693
If you are to achieve
what we have agreed.

552
00:31:53,868 --> 00:31:55,563
Do you understand?

553
00:31:55,737 --> 00:31:57,762
Yes, I understand, Excellency.

554
00:31:57,939 --> 00:31:59,270
Then finish your dinner and get to bed.

555
00:31:59,441 --> 00:32:03,241
Work begins again in the morning.

556
00:32:03,411 --> 00:32:05,242
And now, royal etiquette.

557
00:32:05,413 --> 00:32:09,907
All right...
1, 1, 2, 3, 4.

558
00:32:11,152 --> 00:32:12,779
A queen.

559
00:32:12,954 --> 00:32:15,980
Your Majesty.
A prince of royal blood.

560
00:32:16,157 --> 00:32:17,852
Your Highness.
A prince of ordinary station

561
00:32:18,026 --> 00:32:19,220
Outside of the royal family.

562
00:32:19,394 --> 00:32:21,988
Prince, I suppose, or your Excellency.

563
00:32:22,163 --> 00:32:23,130
This is absurd!

564
00:32:23,298 --> 00:32:25,766
Even Anna Corev wouldn't know all of it!
Pick up the book.

565
00:32:25,934 --> 00:32:28,994
But why do I need it?
Pick up the book.

566
00:32:29,170 --> 00:32:31,536
Put it on your head and walk over there.

567
00:32:31,706 --> 00:32:33,333
You don't seem to realize
that the gesture,

568
00:32:33,508 --> 00:32:35,271
The grace, the carriage
of a true daughter of a tsar...

569
00:32:35,443 --> 00:32:36,774
Cannot be taught.

570
00:32:36,945 --> 00:32:39,505
Either she learns
as a child how to hold herself,

571
00:32:39,681 --> 00:32:45,677
Or it's too late, Excellency.

572
00:32:48,123 --> 00:32:50,057
Did she like to play as a child?

573
00:32:50,225 --> 00:32:52,659
No, but your mother wanted you to.

574
00:32:52,827 --> 00:32:54,988
I still don't like it.

575
00:32:55,163 --> 00:32:57,256
My hands don't have
the strength anymore.

576
00:32:57,432 --> 00:32:59,457
All right. We can use that
as an explanation,

577
00:32:59,634 --> 00:33:03,798
But listen to this.
Now, this is important.

578
00:33:03,972 --> 00:33:05,166
Your tutor wanted you to learn this

579
00:33:05,340 --> 00:33:08,036
To prove to your mother

580
00:33:08,209 --> 00:33:12,509
That the lessons were not in vain.

581
00:33:12,680 --> 00:33:14,705
Did I ever learn it?

582
00:33:14,883 --> 00:33:18,876
Yes, but you hated it.

583
00:33:33,168 --> 00:33:35,568
I like it now.

584
00:33:35,737 --> 00:33:39,730
It's quite pretty.

585
00:34:01,429 --> 00:34:04,262
Now around.
That's it.

586
00:34:04,432 --> 00:34:07,424
Once more.

587
00:34:09,337 --> 00:34:11,635
All right. Now the polonaise.
Can't I rest?

588
00:34:11,806 --> 00:34:13,569
Yes. After dinner. Here we go.

589
00:34:13,741 --> 00:34:16,835
I can't.
You will. Head up. Back straight.

590
00:34:17,011 --> 00:34:19,138
1, 2, 3.

591
00:34:19,314 --> 00:34:23,683
1, 2, 3.
1, 2, 3.

592
00:34:23,851 --> 00:34:26,513
Please.
Please concentrate.

593
00:34:26,688 --> 00:34:28,588
And 1, 2, 3.

594
00:34:28,756 --> 00:34:31,247
1, 2, 3.
My feet hurt. I can't anymore.

595
00:34:31,426 --> 00:34:33,121
A little rest, perhaps...
There is no time.

596
00:34:33,294 --> 00:34:34,625
New waltz, Petrovanch. Come on.

597
00:34:34,796 --> 00:34:36,593
I'm sure you won't mind doing this.

598
00:34:36,764 --> 00:34:38,288
This is the waltz you like so much.

599
00:34:38,466 --> 00:34:43,961
The back. The back.
With ease, with style.

600
00:34:48,543 --> 00:34:50,602
Didn't you say the other day
it reminded you of something?

601
00:34:50,778 --> 00:34:53,042
Yes. Of my first ball.

602
00:34:53,214 --> 00:34:54,772
And your first love, no doubt.

603
00:34:54,949 --> 00:34:57,440
Yes.

604
00:34:57,619 --> 00:35:02,113
Who was he?
I can't remember.

605
00:35:02,624 --> 00:35:06,424
Was he fair,
Or was he dark with a moustache?

606
00:35:06,594 --> 00:35:08,255
I don't know.

607
00:35:08,429 --> 00:35:11,125
One day he's fair, the next he's dark.

608
00:35:11,299 --> 00:35:14,291
I don't know.

609
00:35:20,642 --> 00:35:26,137
1, 2, 3. 1, 2, 3.
1, 2, 3. 1, 2, 3.

610
00:35:57,478 --> 00:36:00,470
Aah!

611
00:36:21,302 --> 00:36:22,360
What are you doing here?

612
00:36:22,537 --> 00:36:24,164
I can't anymore.

613
00:36:24,339 --> 00:36:26,603
I don't know who I am anymore!

614
00:36:26,774 --> 00:36:29,743
I don't know what I remember
or what I've been told I remember!

615
00:36:29,911 --> 00:36:31,879
What is real? Am I?

616
00:36:32,046 --> 00:36:33,877
Anna.
Anna. Am I Anna?

617
00:36:34,048 --> 00:36:37,142
Why not Tamara? Why not Liza?
Why not Tatiana?

618
00:36:37,318 --> 00:36:39,081
Yes. Why not Tatiana?

619
00:36:39,253 --> 00:36:40,982
Oh, I can't anymore.
I don't want this.

620
00:36:41,155 --> 00:36:43,248
I want to be me, whoever I am.
I want to be me.

621
00:36:43,424 --> 00:36:45,517
I want someone to tell me,
someone to accept me.

622
00:36:45,693 --> 00:36:47,752
Look, you have been working very hard,
and you are overtired,

623
00:36:47,929 --> 00:36:49,089
But we're almost finished now.

624
00:36:49,263 --> 00:36:51,163
Are you? Oh, then you know who I am.

625
00:36:51,332 --> 00:36:53,425
A good night's sleep...
You must know! You must!

626
00:36:53,601 --> 00:36:56,365
Just go to bed.
No! I'm leaving! I'm leaving!

627
00:36:56,537 --> 00:36:59,529
Stop it!

628
00:36:59,707 --> 00:37:03,700
Go to bed at once!

629
00:37:14,489 --> 00:37:17,583
My father was very strict.

630
00:37:17,759 --> 00:37:24,255
I did not like to obey,
but he was ringmaster in the circus.

631
00:37:26,501 --> 00:37:28,332
General Boynin.

632
00:37:28,503 --> 00:37:30,232
Yes?

633
00:37:30,405 --> 00:37:33,397
Who am I?

634
00:37:34,308 --> 00:37:37,072
I don't know.

635
00:37:37,245 --> 00:37:39,770
Their Excellencies
Countess Uradif and daughter

636
00:37:39,947 --> 00:37:41,175
And Prince Tergancev.

637
00:37:41,349 --> 00:37:45,115
My dear Madame, her Highness
and the general will be here shortly.

638
00:37:45,286 --> 00:37:48,312
May I thank you again for all of us
for what you're doing.

639
00:37:48,489 --> 00:37:49,456
I should not be thanked.

640
00:37:49,624 --> 00:37:51,683
It makes me happy to do anything

641
00:37:51,859 --> 00:37:52,325
That will help restore
what is rightfully...

642
00:37:52,493 --> 00:37:54,825
Yes.
Oh, Excellency.

643
00:37:54,996 --> 00:37:56,725
His Excellency General Cavelefsky.

644
00:37:56,898 --> 00:38:00,026
I cannot tell you how important
your presence is here today.

645
00:38:00,201 --> 00:38:02,635
My dear Vivina,
I promised your late father

646
00:38:02,804 --> 00:38:06,706
I'd keep an eye on you.
On occasion, it's a little trying.

647
00:38:06,874 --> 00:38:07,898
I promise you will not regret coming.

648
00:38:08,075 --> 00:38:11,306
That's a promise you may have
some difficulty in keeping.

649
00:38:11,479 --> 00:38:13,913
May I sit down?
Do, please.

650
00:38:14,081 --> 00:38:16,015
This abominable gout.

651
00:38:16,184 --> 00:38:17,048
This way.

652
00:38:17,218 --> 00:38:20,881
Albert, a chair for his Excellency.

653
00:38:21,055 --> 00:38:22,488
Take care of his Excellency.

654
00:38:22,657 --> 00:38:25,785
You know how he is.
Baron and baroness Ryobi.

655
00:38:25,960 --> 00:38:27,393
The old fox himself.

656
00:38:27,562 --> 00:38:31,999
I never thought he would come.
Well, we may wish he hadn't.

657
00:38:32,166 --> 00:38:34,225
How many are you taking?

658
00:38:34,402 --> 00:38:35,596
People will think you're hungry.

659
00:38:35,770 --> 00:38:37,237
Hungry? Well, I'm not hungry.

660
00:38:37,405 --> 00:38:39,498
I'm nervous. No, thank you.

661
00:38:39,674 --> 00:38:41,574
His Excellency Count Razumov.

662
00:38:41,742 --> 00:38:45,769
Xenia!
Misha!

663
00:38:45,947 --> 00:38:48,438
I must say, a truly wonderful occasion.

664
00:38:48,616 --> 00:38:50,049
Yes.
What?

665
00:38:50,218 --> 00:38:51,515
Red caviar.
You mean...

666
00:38:51,686 --> 00:38:53,278
Yes.
If the caviar were real...

667
00:38:53,454 --> 00:38:57,891
She would be real.
Your Excellency, remain here, please.

668
00:38:58,059 --> 00:38:59,959
Remain here, your Excellency.

669
00:39:00,127 --> 00:39:02,755
Remain here!
We will see that they come to you.

670
00:39:02,930 --> 00:39:05,091
I understand.
So many old faces.

671
00:39:05,266 --> 00:39:07,496
Yes. And it is their dear
old names we want...

672
00:39:07,668 --> 00:39:10,660
Huh?
We want their names on signed statements

673
00:39:10,838 --> 00:39:12,305
That will convince the bank...

674
00:39:12,473 --> 00:39:13,303
Yes.

675
00:39:13,474 --> 00:39:16,307
Her Imperial Highness,
the Grand Duchess Anastasia.

676
00:39:16,477 --> 00:39:18,138
This way, your Highness.

677
00:39:18,312 --> 00:39:19,574
Francois, the Alcove.

678
00:39:19,747 --> 00:39:22,443
My dear general,
this is all so exciting.

679
00:39:22,617 --> 00:39:25,381
Your Imperial Highness, please.

680
00:39:25,553 --> 00:39:27,077
Well, Petrovanch.

681
00:39:27,255 --> 00:39:30,747
Here we go.
Ladies and gentlemen,

682
00:39:30,925 --> 00:39:33,223
Dear friends,

683
00:39:33,394 --> 00:39:34,383
Oh, I would like to say a few words...

684
00:39:34,562 --> 00:39:36,189
Too much. She's doing too much.

685
00:39:36,364 --> 00:39:39,026
It's very difficult for me to speak today.

686
00:39:39,200 --> 00:39:41,668
General Boynin, would you please?

687
00:39:41,836 --> 00:39:43,064
As you all know, I am the last one

688
00:39:43,237 --> 00:39:44,966
To believe in miracles or resurrections.

689
00:39:45,139 --> 00:39:47,334
But reality cannot be
established without help,

690
00:39:47,508 --> 00:39:50,671
Legal help... witnessed
and signed statements.

691
00:39:50,845 --> 00:39:53,473
It is, frankly, our hope, our need,

692
00:39:53,648 --> 00:39:54,706
That those among you who believe

693
00:39:54,882 --> 00:39:56,213
Will come forward after the reception

694
00:39:56,384 --> 00:40:00,013
And sign these testimonials voluntarily.

695
00:40:00,187 --> 00:40:05,716
Now, I'm quite sure that some of you
have come here to obstruct.

696
00:40:05,893 --> 00:40:09,488
The reasons... political, monetary,
we all know.

697
00:40:09,664 --> 00:40:11,529
There are some who have been made

698
00:40:11,699 --> 00:40:14,031
Understandably cynical
by the revolution,

699
00:40:14,201 --> 00:40:15,634
And there are some

700
00:40:15,803 --> 00:40:19,466
Who will testify to anyone
and anything... and have.

701
00:40:19,640 --> 00:40:21,870
To none of you do we bring any pressure.

702
00:40:22,043 --> 00:40:23,408
To all of you, we bring someone

703
00:40:23,578 --> 00:40:27,537
Who has literally suffered wors
than death for 1o lost years.

704
00:40:27,715 --> 00:40:29,945
It is our duty to restore
this extraordinary person

705
00:40:30,117 --> 00:40:31,675
To the world of the living.

706
00:40:31,852 --> 00:40:35,379
If you are sentimental, say it is
because she has suffered enough.

707
00:40:35,556 --> 00:40:37,956
If you are humane,
say justice must be done.

708
00:40:38,125 --> 00:40:41,561
If you are Russian,
a loyal subject of his late Majesty,

709
00:40:41,729 --> 00:40:45,597
Then say with me,
"our only hope is his daughter,

710
00:40:45,766 --> 00:40:49,429
Her Imperial Highness,
Anastasia Nikolayevna."

711
00:40:49,604 --> 00:40:52,072
Her Excellency Countess Voronova.

712
00:40:52,239 --> 00:40:56,573
Your Highness, when Irina...
when Madame Deresianskaia told me,

713
00:40:56,744 --> 00:40:58,712
I confess I really had doubts.

714
00:40:58,879 --> 00:41:00,141
You can understand.

715
00:41:00,314 --> 00:41:02,805
It really is a miracle.
Is it?

716
00:41:02,984 --> 00:41:04,008
Yes, your Highness.

717
00:41:04,185 --> 00:41:05,209
We met only once...

718
00:41:05,386 --> 00:41:07,581
I remember.
Near the tennis courts at Livaldia.

719
00:41:07,755 --> 00:41:10,622
Yes.
I also remember that my uncle Alex

720
00:41:10,791 --> 00:41:12,725
Got you the title
because he liked dancing.

721
00:41:12,893 --> 00:41:14,224
But from then on,
you made a fool of him.

722
00:41:14,395 --> 00:41:16,522
My mother never liked you,
My father never liked you,

723
00:41:16,697 --> 00:41:18,324
And I never liked you. Please go.

724
00:41:18,499 --> 00:41:20,967
Now, just a moment.
You're not Anastasia yet,

725
00:41:21,135 --> 00:41:26,072
And if I have...
I said please go!

726
00:41:26,240 --> 00:41:28,299
You are mad.
Don't answer.

727
00:41:28,476 --> 00:41:30,944
But I warn you for the last time.

728
00:41:31,112 --> 00:41:33,979
Your Excellency, you're not leaving
without seeing her Highness.

729
00:41:34,148 --> 00:41:35,137
I have seen her.

730
00:41:35,316 --> 00:41:38,479
Oh, but she will be so disappointed
at not having seen you again.

731
00:41:38,653 --> 00:41:41,679
And how do you know that?
Huh? You mean how do I...

732
00:41:41,856 --> 00:41:44,450
Truthfully, Excellency, we don't,
but we're sure she will.

733
00:41:44,625 --> 00:41:45,649
We're sure, Excellency.

734
00:41:45,826 --> 00:41:48,420
And I. Dear Ivan Vaselevich,
you stayed this long,

735
00:41:48,596 --> 00:41:50,086
And after all, you did promise me...

736
00:41:50,264 --> 00:41:52,824
Now, don't wheedle, Irina.
Oh, all right.

737
00:41:53,000 --> 00:41:54,490
But don't try to keep me there too long.

738
00:41:54,669 --> 00:41:57,661
My foot hurts.

739
00:41:58,139 --> 00:42:02,906
I think you are due for a surprise.

740
00:42:03,077 --> 00:42:06,342
His Excellency...
I'm so glad to see you, Ivan Vaselevich.

741
00:42:06,514 --> 00:42:08,448
They told you my name. How kind.

742
00:42:08,616 --> 00:42:09,742
Won't you sit down?

743
00:42:09,917 --> 00:42:12,545
No, thank you. I don't expect to stay.

744
00:42:12,720 --> 00:42:15,450
My father's chamberlain
was a man of great courtesy.

745
00:42:15,623 --> 00:42:18,353
His Majesty complimented me
on many things.

746
00:42:18,526 --> 00:42:20,926
I don't recall his mentioning courtesy.

747
00:42:21,095 --> 00:42:23,222
My father's chamberlain
was also a temperate man

748
00:42:23,397 --> 00:42:24,625
Who did not judge before...

749
00:42:24,799 --> 00:42:27,131
Madame, forgive me.
I've a miserable attack of gout

750
00:42:27,301 --> 00:42:29,895
Undoubtedly a punishment
for being intemperate,

751
00:42:30,071 --> 00:42:33,040
And I'm eager to return to
my tub of hot water.

752
00:42:33,207 --> 00:42:35,505
There are many characteristics
which you could recall,

753
00:42:35,676 --> 00:42:38,804
Many details,
but so could dozens of others.

754
00:42:38,979 --> 00:42:42,813
My relations with His Majesty's
children were impersonal, public.

755
00:42:42,983 --> 00:42:43,608
So in the end,

756
00:42:43,784 --> 00:42:45,649
My judgment can only be
a matter of opinion,

757
00:42:45,820 --> 00:42:49,517
And that opinion can only be determined
by resemblance and manner.

758
00:42:49,690 --> 00:42:52,056
Your Excellency,
1o years is a long time.

759
00:42:52,226 --> 00:42:54,456
No. I've already noted the resemblance.

760
00:42:54,628 --> 00:42:57,825
As for the manner, I've been watching,

761
00:42:57,998 --> 00:42:59,795
And you give me pleasure.

762
00:42:59,967 --> 00:43:01,730
You've taken me back to my seat

763
00:43:01,902 --> 00:43:04,427
In the imperial theater
at St. Petersburg.

764
00:43:04,605 --> 00:43:07,506
Second row on the aisle
every Tuesday night.

765
00:43:07,675 --> 00:43:11,133
For the purpose of acting
is not only to imitate reality,

766
00:43:11,312 --> 00:43:13,405
But to create illusion.

767
00:43:13,581 --> 00:43:15,913
I'm not being sarcastic
when I say that you are

768
00:43:16,083 --> 00:43:20,213
An excellent actress, Madame...
extremely well-trained.

769
00:43:20,387 --> 00:43:22,821
My compliments.
I do not accept them.

770
00:43:22,990 --> 00:43:24,753
Madame, my foot is troubling me.

771
00:43:24,925 --> 00:43:27,689
My life is troubling me,
and it has yet to be lived.

772
00:43:27,862 --> 00:43:30,854
You do not believe
because you do not wish to believe.

773
00:43:31,031 --> 00:43:32,498
You say my words will not convince

774
00:43:32,666 --> 00:43:34,998
Because you're afraid
I know the right words.

775
00:43:35,169 --> 00:43:36,261
You misquote, Madame.

776
00:43:36,437 --> 00:43:39,668
I also said that the manner,
the deportment of a grand duchess

777
00:43:39,840 --> 00:43:43,901
Would convince me,
but I don't see it in you,

778
00:43:44,078 --> 00:43:45,306
Not a gesture,

779
00:43:45,479 --> 00:43:47,845
Though one would be worth
more than all the words

780
00:43:48,015 --> 00:43:49,812
You undoubtedly can produce.

781
00:43:49,984 --> 00:43:52,452
Good day, Madame.

782
00:43:52,620 --> 00:43:59,025
How dare you smoke in my presence
without my permission?

783
00:43:59,193 --> 00:44:01,923
Who are you?

784
00:44:02,096 --> 00:44:08,092
15, 16, 17, 18 out of a possible 51.

785
00:44:09,837 --> 00:44:12,135
And you were so sure
it would be almost a clean sweep.

786
00:44:12,306 --> 00:44:14,866
Didn't the old fox himself
say her performance was great art?

787
00:44:15,042 --> 00:44:17,408
We're not doing this for art.
We're doing it for money.

788
00:44:17,578 --> 00:44:19,341
Now, listen, this can go on forever...

789
00:44:19,513 --> 00:44:21,447
Some saying she is,
some saying she isn't.

790
00:44:21,615 --> 00:44:23,276
Precisely. My mind is made up.

791
00:44:23,450 --> 00:44:25,850
Oh, to what?
There's only one way...

792
00:44:26,020 --> 00:44:26,987
To go straight to the top.

793
00:44:27,154 --> 00:44:30,248
You mean the old icon?
Yes. The dowager empress.

794
00:44:30,424 --> 00:44:31,948
Oh, sure. The old ramrod

795
00:44:32,126 --> 00:44:34,959
Sitting in her castle
in Copenhagen biting her nails

796
